<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920204-0055</DOCNO><DOCID>920204-0055.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Noble Drilling Corp.:   Company Is Laying Off 200   In Its Domestic Work Force</HL><DATE>02/04/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6</SO><CO>   LABOR NDCO</CO><MS>ENERGY (ENE)</MS><IN>OIL-DRILLING AND EXPLORATION (DRL)OIL-EQUIPMENT AND SERVICES (OIE)PETROLEUM (PET)</IN><NS>LABOR, UNIONS, STRIKES, WAGES, RECRUITMENT (LAB)PETROLEUM MARKET (PET)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)OHIO (OH)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Noble Drilling Corp., Houston, said it is laying off 200employees, or about 20% to 25% of its domestic work force.The company is closing its land-drilling operations in themid-continental and Rocky Mountain regions of the U.S. The 29rigs involved will be brought to two centralized locationsand mothballed, a Noble spokesman said.   The drilling contractor said closing these two divisions,which are based in Oklahoma, is part of its strategy toemphasize offshore and international drilling.</LP><TEXT>   Domestic drilling has been depressed for a long period oftime with little improvement seen for the near term, saidJames C. Day, president and chief executive officer of Noble.The domestic service sector of the oil industry will continueto contract and reserves will continue to decline until ourcountry develops a viable national energy policy, he said.</TEXT></DOC>